{"parse":{"title":"Task-invoked pupillary response","pageid":31366637,"revid":857814298,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Eye_dilate.gif\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Eye_dilate.gif/220px-Eye_dilate.gif\" width=\"220\" height=\"126\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Eye_dilate.gif/330px-Eye_dilate.gif 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Eye_dilate.gif/440px-Eye_dilate.gif 2x\" data-file-width=\"640\" data-file-height=\"366\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Eye_dilate.gif\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Pupillary response</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Task-invoked pupillary response</b> (also known as the \"Task-<i>Evoked</i> pupillary response\") is a <a href=\"/wiki/Pupillary_response\" title=\"Pupillary response\">pupillary response</a> caused by a <a href=\"/wiki/Cognitive_load\" title=\"Cognitive load\">cognitive load</a> imposed on a human and as a result of the decrease in <a href=\"/wiki/Parasympathetic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Parasympathetic\">parasympathetic</a> activity in the <a href=\"/wiki/Peripheral_nervous_system\" title=\"Peripheral nervous system\">peripheral nervous system</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It is found to result in a linear increase in pupil dilation as the demand a task places on the working memory increases. Beatty evaluated task-invoked pupillary response in different tasks for short-term memory, language processing, reasoning, perception, sustained attention and selective attention and found that it fulfils Kahneman\u2019s three criteria for indicating processing load.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> That is, it can reflect differences in processing load within a task, between different tasks and between individuals.  It is used as an indicator of cognitive load levels in <a href=\"/wiki/Psychophysiology\" title=\"Psychophysiology\">psychophysiology</a> research.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Task-invoked_pupillary_response&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Kramer, A. F., 1991. Physiological metrics of mental workload: A review of recent progress. In: Damos, D. L. (ed.) <i>Multiple-task Performance</i>. London: Taylor &amp; Francis Ltd.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:0-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Beatty, J., 1982, Task-evoked pupillary responses, processing load, and the structure of processing resources. <i>Psychological Bulletin</i>, 91, 276-292.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Kahneman, D., 1973, <i>Attention and effort</i>, Englewood Cliffs, N. J., Prentice-hall.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Eye_iris.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Eye_iris.jpg/40px-Eye_iris.jpg\" width=\"40\" height=\"27\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Eye_iris.jpg/60px-Eye_iris.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Eye_iris.jpg/80px-Eye_iris.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2788\" data-file-height=\"1864\" /></a></td><td><i>This article about the <a href=\"/wiki/Eye\" title=\"Eye\">eye</a> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Task-invoked_pupillary_response&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Eye-stub\" title=\"Template:Eye-stub\"><abbr title=\"View this template\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:Eye-stub\" title=\"Template talk:Eye-stub\"><abbr title=\"Discuss this template\">t</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-edit\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Eye-stub&amp;action=edit\"><abbr title=\"Edit this template\">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Psi2.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Psi2.svg/30px-Psi2.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Psi2.svg/45px-Psi2.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Psi2.svg/60px-Psi2.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"100\" data-file-height=\"100\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Psychology\" title=\"Psychology\">psycholog